article.headline: LeBron has double-double in loss
article.linkText: Griz pour on Gasol, who lights Cavs for 37
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- LeBron James was the last player to shower, slumping in his chair in an empty locker room. The rookie was in no mood to celebrate his finest game as a pro. That party had been canceled. Pau Gasol scored a career-high 37 points and the Memphis Grizzlies completed their second-biggest comeback with a 122-115 win in double overtime Saturday night over Cleveland. James had a monster performance -- 33 points, 16 rebounds and seven assists -- but made two costly turnovers in the final 1:08 of the first overtime period that helped Memphis rally. "I would have rather been blown out by 50 then lose like this," he said. Cleveland has lost six in a row. At 18 years, 334 days old, James became the youngest player in NBA history to score 30 or more points in a game. Kobe Bryant was the previous youngest, accomplishing the feat in 1997 when he was 19 years, 113 days old. Shane Battier added 22 points and a career-high 12 rebounds for the Grizzlies, who trailed by 24 in the first half and 16 going into the fourth quarter. Memphis' comeback was its biggest since overcoming a 25-point deficit to beat Portland on March 25, 2002. "We're not a team that ever says the game is over," Grizzlies coach Hubie Brown said. Mike Miller added 20 points and a career-high 13 assists for the Grizzlies, who clawed back by scoring the first 18 points of the fourth quarter. "Boy, am I glad we won, we really needed it," said Miller, who was forced to play point guard after Jason Williams went out after four minutes with back spasms. "We're a team that feeds off one another. We make runs. Our style is that hopefully we'll come out ahead." Cleveland's Ricky Davis had 25 points and Zydrunas Ilgauskas 17 before fouling out in the first minute of overtime. James made a steal and dunk with 2:30 left in the first overtime to put the Cavs up 107-102, and it looked as if Cleveland had finally put Memphis away for good. But James, who had a season-high eight turnovers, made two bad passes that led to a layup by Stromile Swift and Gasol's two free throws that got the Grizzlies within 107-106 with 31 seconds left. James then hit a driving left-handed layup with 14.2 seconds left, but the Grizzlies came back again as Miller drained a 3-pointer over Davis with 2 seconds left to tie it. "It felt good, but I was a little deep, so I had to watch it go in," Miller said. "Thank God it went in." James hit a 3-pointer -- his third -- early in the second overtime before the Grizzlies scored six straight points to take a 119-114 lead with 1:23 remaining. The Cavs got within four, and had a chance to get even closer but Davis turned it over in the backcourt and Stromile Swift's dunk with 27 seconds left finally allowed the Grizzlies to relax and celebrate their stunning comeback. "We had our chances, we just didn't execute," Cavs coach Paul Silas said. "It's a very disappointing loss." Memphis had the last chance to win it in regulation, but Miller couldn't get off a layup before the final horn. James missed a fadeaway 25-footer at the horn that would have won it in the first overtime. After trailing 49-25 in the second quarter and 80-64 after three, the Grizzlies opened the fourth quarter with an 18-0 run, opening a 82-80 lead on Battier's 3-pointer with 7:45 remaining. The Cavaliers missed their first 12 shots from the field in the period before J.R. Bremer hit a layup to pull Cleveland within 86-84. Davis hit a 12-foot jumper at the buzzer to end the first quarter and followed in a miss in the final second before half as the Cavs took a 57-41 lead at the break. Coming off a six-point performance on Friday when he got schooled by Pistons guard Richard Hamilton during a loss in Detroit, James stuffed the stat sheet in the first quarter. He recorded 11 points, five rebounds and three assists in helping the Cavaliers open a 35-14 lead after one.

Game notes
The Grizzlies' seven wins in November tied the club record for the month set in 1997. ... Gasol has 78 points and 33 rebounds in his last three games. ... Cavs F Carlos Boozer missed his sixth straight game with a sprained ankle. ... The Cavs will try to end their nearly yearlong road losing streak -- now at 31 games -- at Denver on Tuesday. They'll visit the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday. The NBA record is 43 consecutive road losses, set by Sacramento from 1990-92. ... Grizzlies C Lorenzen Wright missed his second game in a row with a sprained right ankle.
